27'''\n|-\n| align=left|[[Mike Gorman (ice hockey)|Mike Gorman]]\n| align=left|[[Sudbury Wolves]]\n| 12 || 720 || 7 || 5 || 29 || 1 || 0.930 || '''2.42'''\n|}\n\n==All-Star teams==\n\n===First team===\n*[[Dan Tessier]], Centre, [[Ottawa 67's]]\n*[[Taylor Pyatt]], Left Wing, [[Sudbury Wolves]]\n*[[Norm Milley]], Right Wing, [[Sudbury Wolves]]\n*[[John Erskine (ice hockey)|John Erskine]], Defence, [[London Knights]]\n*[[Branislav Mezei]], Defence, [[Belleville Bulls]]\n*[[Andrew Raycroft]], Goaltender, [[Kingston Frontenacs]]\n*[[Peter DeBoer]], Coach, [[Plymouth Whalers]]\n\n===Second team===\n*[[Jason Jaspers]], Centre, [[Sudbury Wolves]]\n*[[Raffi Torres]], Left Wing, [[Brampton Battalion]]\n*[[Sheldon Keefe]], Right Wing, [[Barrie Colts]]\n*[[Allan Rourke]], Defence, [[Kitchener Rangers]]\n*[[Kevin Mitchell (ice hockey)|Kevin Mitchell]], Defence, [[Guelph Storm]]\n*[[Rob Zepp]], Goaltender, [[Plymouth Whalers]]\n*[[Tom Webster (ice hockey)|Tom Webster]], Coach, [[Windsor Spitfires]]\n\n===Third team===\n*[[Josef Vasicek]], Centre, [[Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds]]\n*[[Johnathan Schill]], Left Wing, [[Kingston Frontenacs]]\n*[[Denis Shvidki]], Right Wing, [[Barrie Colts]]\n*[[Alexei Semenov]], Defence, [[Sudbury Wolves]]\n*[[Mike Van Ryn]], Defence, [[Sarnia Sting]]\n*[[Levente Szuper]], Goaltender, [[Ottawa 67's]]\n*[[Stan Butler]], Coach, [[Brampton Battalion]]\n\n==Awards==\n{| cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|[[J. Ross Robertson Cup]]: || [[Barrie Colts]]\n|-\n|[[Hamilton Spectator Trophy]]: || [[Plymouth Whalers]]\n|-\n|[[Bobby Orr Trophy]]: || [[Barrie Colts]]\n|-\n|[[Wayne Gretzky Trophy]]: || [[Plymouth Whalers]]\n|-\n|[[Leyden Trophy]]: || [[Ottawa 67's]]\n|-\n|[[Emms Trophy]]: || [[Barrie Colts]]\n|-\n|[[Holody Trophy]]: || [[Erie Otters]]\n|-\n|[[Bumbacco Trophy]]: || [[Plymouth Whalers]]\n|-\n|[[Red Tilson Trophy]]: || [[Andrew Raycroft]], [[Kingston Frontenacs]]\n|-\n|[[Eddie Powers Memorial Trophy]]: || [[Sheldon Keefe]], [[Barrie Colts]]\n|-\n|[[Matt Leyden Trophy]]: || [[Peter DeBoer]], [[Plymouth Whalers]]\n|-\n|[[Jim Mahon Memorial Trophy]]: || [[Sheldon Keefe]], [[Barrie Colts]]\n|-\n|[[Max Kaminsky Trophy]]: || [[John Erskine (ice hockey)|John Erskine]], [[London Knights]]\n|-\n|[[OHL Goaltender of the Year]]: || [[Andrew Raycroft]], [[Kingston Frontenacs]]\n|-\n|[[Jack Ferguson Award]]: || [[Patrick Jarrett (ice hockey)|Patrick Jarrett]], [[Mississauga IceDogs]]\n|-\n|[[Dave Pinkney Trophy]]: || [[Rob Zepp]] and [[Bill Ruggiero]], [[Plymouth Whalers]]\n|-\n|[[OHL Executive of the Year]]: || [[Robert Ciccarelli]], [[Sarnia Sting]]\n|-\n|[[Emms Family Award]]: || [[Derek Roy]], [[Kitchener Rangers]]\n|-\n|[[F.W. 'Dinty' Moore Trophy]]: || [[Andrew Sim]], [[Sarnia Sting]]\n|-\n|[[Dan Snyder Memorial Trophy|OHL Humanitarian of the Year]]: || [[Dan Tessier]], [[Ottawa 67's]]\n|-\n|[[William Hanley Trophy]]: || [[Mike Zigomanis]], [[Kingston Frontenacs]]\n|-\n|[[Leo Lalonde Memorial Trophy]]: || [[Dan Tessier]], [[Ottawa 67's]]\n|-\n|[[Bobby Smith Trophy]]: || [[Brad Boyes]], [[Erie Otters]]\n|-\n|[[Wayne Gretzky 99 Award]]: || [[Brian Finley]], [[Barrie Colts]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of OHA Junior A standings]]\n*[[List of OHL seasons]]\n*[[2000 Memorial Cup]]\n*[[2000 NHL Entry Draft]]\n*[[1999 in sports]]\n*[[2000 in sports]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://www.hockeydb.com/ihdb/stats/leagues/seasons/ohl19892000.html HockeyDB]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{succession box |\n  before = [[1998\u201399 OHL season]] |\n  after = [[2000\u201301 OHL season]] |\n  title = [[List of OHL seasons|OHL seasons]] |\n  years = |\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{OHL}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1999-2000 Ohl Season}}\n[[Category:Ontario Hockey League seasons]]\n[[Category:1999\u20132000 in Canadian ice hockey by league|OHL]]\n", "name_user": "Frontsfan2005", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e(2) Erie Otters vs. (3) Sault Ste. Marie Greyhounds", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1999%E2%80%932000_OHL_season"}
{"title_page": "Mario Poggi", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Rough translation|1=Spanish|listed=yes|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mario Poggi\n| birth_name         = Mario Augusto Poggi Estremadoyro\n| birth_date         = March 3, 1943\n| birth_place        = [[Barranco District|Barranco]], Lima, Per\u00fa\n| death_date         = February 26, 2016 (aged 72)\n| death_place        = [[Lima]], Per\u00fa\n| nationality        = Peruvian\n| occupation         = Psychologist, sculptor, humorist\n| works              = \n| awards             = \n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20150401172623/http://mariopoggi.blogspot.com/ Mario Poggi Estremadoyro]\n}}\n'''Mario Augusto Poggi Estremadoyro''' ([[Lima]], March 3, 1943 \u2013 February 26, 2016) was a Peruvian [[psychologist]], artist, sculptor and humorist. He became well known for killing an alleged serial killer in 1986; he was arrested for the murder and sentenced to 12 years in prison, but was released in 1991 after serving around 5 years.<ref name=\"Falleci\u00f33\">{{cite news | url = http://elcomercio.pe/lima/sucesos/mario-poggi-fallecio-hoy-sus-73-anos-paro-cardiaco-noticia-1882298 | title = Mario Poggi falleci\u00f3 a sus 73 a\u00f1os por un paro card\u00edaco: El psic\u00f3logo que se volvi\u00f3 famoso en 1986 por estrangular a Hugo D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn sufri\u00f3 dos paros card\u00edacos en cuesti\u00f3n de horas | language = Spanish | trans-title = Mario Poggi died at 73 from cardiac arrest: The psychologist who became famous in 1986 for strangling Hugo D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn suffered two cardiac arrests in a matter of hours | date = February 27, 2016 | work = [[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]] | location = Lima, Peru | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160301040611/http://elcomercio.pe/lima/sucesos/mario-poggi-fallecio-hoy-sus-73-anos-paro-cardiaco-noticia-1882298 | archive-date = March 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Crime ===\n<!-- sources added for crime section! not gonna clean up the ordering, that's just too much XD -->\nFrom December 1985 to February 1986, dismembered human body parts, mainly female, were discovered in black bags in trashcans and alleyways around Lima, Peru.<ref name=\":0\" /> The remains were thought to belong to at least seven different victims, and potentially up to twenty. The [[Peruvian National Police]] (\"Polic\u00eda de Investigaciones del Per\u00fa,\" PIP) suspected 30-year-old<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/el-mundo/la-escalofriante-historia-del-psicologo-quiso-ser-nid2189153|title=La historia del psic\u00f3logo que quiso ser h\u00e9roe y asesin\u00f3 a su paciente|date=2018-11-16|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://elcomercio.pe/blog/huellasdigitales/2011/02/mario-poggi-o-el-histrion-de-l/|title=Mario Poggi o el histri\u00f3n de la muerte {{!}} Blog|website=El Comercio Per\u00fa|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1986/02/10/A-psychiatrist-convinced-by-a-battery-of-tests-that/9444508395600/|title=A psychiatrist, convinced by a battery of tests that...|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \u00c1ngel D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn (some sources reported Hugo D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expreso.com.pe/actualidad/fallecio-psicologo-mario-poggi-mejor-conocido-como-loco|title=Falleci\u00f3 psic\u00f3logo Mario Poggi, mejor conocido como \u201cLoco\u201d|website=Expreso|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://peru21.pe/lima/mario-poggi-fallecio-73-anos-paro-cardiaco-211822-noticia/|title=Mario Poggi falleci\u00f3 a los 73 a\u00f1os por un paro card\u00edaco|last=Peru21|first=Redacci\u00f3n|date=2016-02-27|website=Peru21|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> of the crime.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://elcomercio.pe/lima/mario-poggi-asesinato-descuartizador-lima-277283-noticia/|title=Mario Poggi y el asesinato del \u201cdescuartizador de Lima\u201d|last=Per\u00fa|first=Redacci\u00f3n El Comercio|date=2016-02-27|website=El Comercio Per\u00fa|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.notimerica.com/sociedad/noticia-conoces-terrible-historia-descuartizador-lima-psicologo-loco-20170209071743.html|title=\u00bfConoces la terrible historia del descuartizador de Lima y su psic\u00f3logo 'loco'?|last=Press|first=Europa|date=2017-02-09|website=www.notimerica.com|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.notimerica.com/sociedad/noticia-mario-poggi-psicologo-mato-asesino-20180226115551.html|title=Mario Poggi, el psic\u00f3logo que mat\u00f3 al asesino|last=Press|first=Europa|date=2018-02-26|website=www.notimerica.com|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> A decade earlier in 1976, D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn had been convicted of killing his aunt and two of his cousins, and was also suspected of killing another woman.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn had gotten out of prison shortly before the body parts began showing up.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nIn early February 1986, police arrested D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn on suspicion of his involvement, but could not get him to confess. Frustrated, they requested help from Poggi, who had been working as a psychologist in Europe<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> and had previously worked for the PIP as a professor at the Center of Instruction (\"El Centro de Instrucci\u00f3n), also called the Officer School (\"Escuela De Oficiales\").<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nPoggi interrogated D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn for four days but was unable to elicit a confession.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> According to some sources, the police had asked Poggi to get a confession by using the \"scientific methods\" of the [[Nazis]] in the [[second world war]] (i.e., [[torture]]),<ref name=\":0\" /> but he still would not confess. On 7 February (the fourth day of interrogations), Poggi met with journalists from the [[Caretas]] newsmagazine (either two people<ref name=\":0\" /> or just Jorge Salazar)<ref name=\":1\" /> and offered them an exclusive scoop on D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn, as well as tapes from the interrogations, in return for payment.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> (However, one source says Poggi met with them \"hours before committing the crime.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320125927/http://www.caretas.com.pe/2000/1644/articulos/policiales.phtml|title=50 A\u00f1os De Policiales|last=|first=|date=2012-03-20|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Poggi received a check for half the agreed upon amount.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe following day, on 9 February 1986, Poggi threw D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn to the ground and tightened a belt around his neck until he suffocated.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Strangely, body parts kept showing up even after D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn's death.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> (Although one source claims there weren't any murders after.)<ref name=\":5\" /> Poggi was subsequently found guilty and sentenced to seven years in prison. He was released after five years in 1991.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nPoggi's motive for the crime is unclear. Many sources state that Poggi decided to kill D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn because he feared there was not enough evidence to prove D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn was the [[serial killer]], as the key witness who claimed to have seen D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn placing body parts in a trash bin decided not to testify. Believing D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn was the dangerous serial killer, Poggi killed him to prevent him from going free.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1986-02-13-0200080277-story.html|title=CONFESSION TOO MUCH|last=Sentinel|first=Orlando|website=OrlandoSentinel.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> On the other hand, the Peruvian journalist Enrique Sol alleged that Poggi told him during an interview that he killed D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn to prevent his publicizing the illegal torture methods Poggi had used.<ref name=\":0\" /> Also, in one interview Poggi allegedly claimed the police, frustrated at not getting a confession, had killed D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn and manipulated the [[autopsy]] to make it look like he was strangled. In this account, Poggi then agreed to take the blame for the crime after being told he would only spend four months in jail and that prison would allow him to study the psychology of the other prisoners.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=Marrison|first=James|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KSGtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT149&lpg=PT149&dq=angel+diaz+balbin&source=bl&ots=poviZ8LkuQ&sig=ACfU3U20K007ESv8sryWIYR1EIlKpOVLVg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjLtcHJ0-noAhW7knIEHf1tB8kQ6AEwEHoECAkQKQ#v=onepage&q=angel%20diaz%20balbin&f=false|title=The World's Most Bizarre Murders|date=2010-06-07|publisher=Kings Road Publishing|isbn=978-1-84358-698-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to one source, during the final interrogation, Poggi disrobed himself and D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn (who was tied up), attempting to sexually provoke D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn into confessing and showing Poggi how he raped his victims before killing them. However, D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn still did not confess.<!-- I think this is the author misrepresenting the truth. Based on blogs and such, it seems that this \"sexual\" account of the murder is portrayed in Poggi's semi-autobiographical movie, Mi Crimen Desnudo. The movie notably exaggerated and fictionalized a lot of elements, so perhaps the author mistakenly thought it was true? That's my hunch. --><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Celebrity ===\nIn 1991, Poggi was released from jail. He decided to stay away from psychology after being released. He called himself \"Loco\" (Crazy), and dyed his hair green. He then became a celebrity. He was invited on to several television programs, many having poor ratings, and that looked for a \"sensational\" introduction or central topic.\n\nIn 1997, Poggi published his autobiography, \"''I Only Know I Am A Moron''\"(\"''Yo S\u00f3lo S\u00e9 Que Soy Un Imb\u00e9cil''), in a poor quality format with green ink and recurrent spelling, typographical and edition errors that according to the newspaper, El Siglo, was to show respect to the original message. It consisted of an introductory chapter with delusional quotes and some passages of his life \u2015 where he mixes popular characters and celebrities from the culture of Lima. The final chapter contained some of his drawings and some art critiques of his sculptures.\n\nIn 2000, Poggi participated in the filming of the movie ''My Nude Crime''\"(''Mi Crimen Al Desnudo''\"), by Le\u00f3nidas Zegarra, in which he played himself. The film was released in 2001. The project began in 1998, when a group of film students wanted to bring to the big screen the story of the murder of the serial criminal Angel D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn at the hands of psychologist Mario Poggi. Zegarra was invited to participate in the project as the director. The film's production was financed mainly by loans. The equipment needed was acquired in agreement with a production company. The budget, like in every movie by Zegarra, was  just $11.000 (equivalent to $16,388.72 as of 2019). Because of that, according to Zegarra, they came to an agreement with the actors and actresses (Mario Poggi, Am\u00e9rico Z\u00fa\u00f1iga, Yesabella, Rossi War, V\u00edctor \u00c1ngeles y Wilmer Ato) to pay them when the movie was commercialized, and when they retrieved the money invested. The movie also featured the well-known Peruvian singer [[La Tigresa del Oriente]] (In English: The Eastern Tigress) portraying [[Magaly Medina]], who became famous in the next decade for her music videos on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://larepublica.pe/blogs/camaleon_con_zapatillas/2009/09/25/la-otra-tigresa-del-oriente-la-felina-que-no-colgo-su-video-en-youtube/|title= La otra Tigresa del Oriente: la felina que no colg\u00f3 su video en Youtube | first = Alfredo | last = P\u00e9rez Andrade | date=September 25, 2008 | language = Spanish | trans-title = The other Eastern Tigress: the feline who did not upload her video on YouTube |publisher=La Rep\u00fablica| url-status = dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712062644/http://larepublica.pe/blogs/camaleon_con_zapatillas/2009/09/25/la-otra-tigresa-del-oriente-la-felina-que-no-colgo-su-video-en-youtube/|archive-date=July 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Death ===\nAccording the [[testimony]] of Poggi's brother, Mario Poggi suffered a cardiac arrest<ref name=\"Falleci\u00f33\"/> the night of February 25, 2016. He was taken to the [[:es:Hospital de Emergencias Jos\u00e9 Casimiro Ulloa|Casimiro Ulloa Hospital]], Lima. He died there of another cardiac arrest the next day at noon on February 26, 2016, just five days prior to his 73rd birthday.\n\nHis remains were laid in the Virgen de F\u00e1tima church in [[Miraflores District, Lima]].\n\n== Books ==\n\n* 1970: Mi Primer Pajazo. (My First Handjob)\n* 1975: Yo solo s\u00e9 que soy un imb\u00e9cil (I only know I'm a Moron) Autobiographic Text. Lima (Per\u00fa): Editorial El Siglo (The Century Publisher), 1997.\n* 1990s: El dec\u00e1logo de la correa vengadora (The Dechaloge of the Avenger Belt) Text on which he refers to the belt which he used in the Balbin's Killing.\n\n==Film==\n\n*2001: Mi crimen al desnudo (My Nude Crime). Directed by Leonidas Zegarra.\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Peruvian psychologists]]\n[[Category:People from Lima]]\n[[Category:Peruvian writers]]\n[[Category:Peruvian criminals]]\n[[Category:Peruvian murderers]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Rough translation|1=Spanish|listed=yes|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mario Poggi\n| birth_name         = Mario Augusto Poggi Estremadoyro\n| birth_date         = March 3, 1943\n| birth_place        = [[Barranco District|Barranco]], Lima, Per\u00fa\n| death_date         = February 26, 2016 (aged 72)\n| death_place        = [[Lima]], Per\u00fa\n| nationality        = Peruvian\n| occupation         = Psychologist, sculptor, humorist\n| works              = \n| awards             = \n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20150401172623/http://mariopoggi.blogspot.com/ Mario Poggi Estremadoyro]\n}}\n'''Mario Augusto Poggi Estremadoyro''' ([[Lima]], March 3, 1943 \u2013 February 26, 2016) was a Peruvian [[psychologist]], artist, sculptor and humorist. He became well known for killing an alleged serial killer in 1986; he was arrested for the murder and sentenced to 12 years in prison, but was released in 1991 after serving around 5 years.<ref name=\"Falleci\u00f33\">{{cite news | url = http://elcomercio.pe/lima/sucesos/mario-poggi-fallecio-hoy-sus-73-anos-paro-cardiaco-noticia-1882298 | title = Mario Poggi falleci\u00f3 a sus 73 a\u00f1os por un paro card\u00edaco: El psic\u00f3logo que se volvi\u00f3 famoso en 1986 por estrangular a Hugo D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn sufri\u00f3 dos paros card\u00edacos en cuesti\u00f3n de horas | language = Spanish | trans-title = Mario Poggi died at 73 from cardiac arrest: The psychologist who became famous in 1986 for strangling Hugo D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn suffered two cardiac arrests in a matter of hours | date = February 27, 2016 | work = [[El Comercio (Peru)|El Comercio]] | location = Lima, Peru | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160301040611/http://elcomercio.pe/lima/sucesos/mario-poggi-fallecio-hoy-sus-73-anos-paro-cardiaco-noticia-1882298 | archive-date = March 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Crime ===\n<!-- sources added for crime section! not gonna clean up the ordering, that's just too much XD -->\nThe Polic\u00eda de Investigaciones del Per\u00fa (Peruvian national police, PIP) suspected 30-year-old<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lanacion.com.ar/el-mundo/la-escalofriante-historia-del-psicologo-quiso-ser-nid2189153|title=La historia del psic\u00f3logo que quiso ser h\u00e9roe y asesin\u00f3 a su paciente|date=2018-11-16|website=www.lanacion.com.ar|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://elcomercio.pe/blog/huellasdigitales/2011/02/mario-poggi-o-el-histrion-de-l/|title=Mario Poggi o el histri\u00f3n de la muerte {{!}} Blog|website=El Comercio Per\u00fa|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1986/02/10/A-psychiatrist-convinced-by-a-battery-of-tests-that/9444508395600/|title=A psychiatrist, convinced by a battery of tests that...|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> \u00c1ngel D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn (some sources call him Hugo D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.expreso.com.pe/actualidad/fallecio-psicologo-mario-poggi-mejor-conocido-como-loco|title=Falleci\u00f3 psic\u00f3logo Mario Poggi, mejor conocido como \u201cLoco\u201d|website=Expreso|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://peru21.pe/lima/mario-poggi-fallecio-73-anos-paro-cardiaco-211822-noticia/|title=Mario Poggi falleci\u00f3 a los 73 a\u00f1os por un paro card\u00edaco|last=Peru21|first=Redacci\u00f3n|date=2016-02-27|website=Peru21|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> of the crime.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://elcomercio.pe/lima/mario-poggi-asesinato-descuartizador-lima-277283-noticia/|title=Mario Poggi y el asesinato del \u201cdescuartizador de Lima\u201d|last=Per\u00fa|first=Redacci\u00f3n El Comercio|date=2016-02-27|website=El Comercio Per\u00fa|language=es|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.notimerica.com/sociedad/noticia-conoces-terrible-historia-descuartizador-lima-psicologo-loco-20170209071743.html|title=\u00bfConoces la terrible historia del descuartizador de Lima y su psic\u00f3logo 'loco'?|last=Press|first=Europa|date=2017-02-09|website=www.notimerica.com|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.notimerica.com/sociedad/noticia-mario-poggi-psicologo-mato-asesino-20180226115551.html|title=Mario Poggi, el psic\u00f3logo que mat\u00f3 al asesino|last=Press|first=Europa|date=2018-02-26|website=www.notimerica.com|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> A decade earlier in 1976, D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn had been convicted of killing his aunt and two of his cousins, and he was also suspected of killing another woman.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn had gotten out of prison shortly before the body parts began showing up.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nIn early February 1986, police arrested D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn on suspicion of his involvement, but could not get him to confess. Frustrated, they requested help from Poggi, who had been working as a psychologist in Europe<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> and had previously worked for the PIP as a professor at the Center of Instruction (\"El Centro de Instrucci\u00f3n), also called the Officer School (\"Escuela De Oficiales\").<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nPoggi interrogated D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn for 4 days but was unable to elicit a confession.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> According to some sources, the police had asked Poggi to get a confession by using the \"scientific methods\" of the Nazis in the second world war (i.e., torture),<ref name=\":0\" /> but he still would not confess. On 7 February (the fourth day of interrogations), Poggi met with journalists from the Caretas newsmagazine (either two people<ref name=\":0\" /> or just Jorge Salazar)<ref name=\":1\" /> and offered them an exclusive scoop on D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn, as well as tapes from the interrogations, in return for payment.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> (However, one source says Poggi met with them \"hours before committing the crime.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320125927/http://www.caretas.com.pe/2000/1644/articulos/policiales.phtml|title=50 A\u00f1os De Policiales|last=|first=|date=2012-03-20|website=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Poggi received a check for half the agreed upon amount.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe following day, on 9 February 1986, Poggi threw D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn to the ground and tightened a belt around his neck until he suffocated.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Strangely, body parts kept showing up even after D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn's death.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> (Although one source claims there weren't any murders after.)<ref name=\":5\" /> Poggi was subsequently found guilty and sentenced to 7 years in prison. He was released after 5 years in 1991.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nPoggi's motive for the crime is unclear. Many sources state that Poggi decided to kill D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn because he feared there was not enough evidence to prove D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn was the serial killer, as the key witness who claimed to have seen D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn placing body parts in a trash bin decided not to testify. Believing D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn was the dangerous serial killer, Poggi killed him to prevent him from going free.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1986-02-13-0200080277-story.html|title=CONFESSION TOO MUCH|last=Sentinel|first=Orlando|website=OrlandoSentinel.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> On the other hand, the Peruvian journalist Enrique Sol alleged that Poggi told him during an interview that he killed D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn to prevent his publicizing the illegal torture methods Poggi had used.<ref name=\":0\" /> Also, in one interview Poggi allegedly claimed the police, frustrated at not getting a confession, had killed D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn and manipulated the autopsy to make it look like he was strangled. In this account, Poggi then agreed to take the blame for the crime after being told he would only spend 4 months in jail and that prison would allow him to study the psychology of the other prisoners.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=Marrison|first=James|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KSGtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT149&lpg=PT149&dq=angel+diaz+balbin&source=bl&ots=poviZ8LkuQ&sig=ACfU3U20K007ESv8sryWIYR1EIlKpOVLVg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjLtcHJ0-noAhW7knIEHf1tB8kQ6AEwEHoECAkQKQ#v=onepage&q=angel%20diaz%20balbin&f=false|title=The World's Most Bizarre Murders|date=2010-06-07|publisher=Kings Road Publishing|isbn=978-1-84358-698-2|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to one source, during the final interrogation, Poggi disrobed himself and D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn (who was tied up), attempting to sexually provoke D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn into confessing and showing Poggi how he raped his victims before killing them. However, D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn still did not confess.<!-- I think this is the author misrepresenting the truth. Based on blogs and such, it seems that this \"sexual\" account of the murder is portrayed in Poggi's semi-autobiographical movie, Mi Crimen Desnudo. The movie notably exaggerated and fictionalized a lot of elements, so perhaps the author mistakenly thought it was true? That's my hunch. --><ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== Celebrity ===\nIn 1991, Poggi was released from jail. He decided to stay away from psychology after being released. He called himself \"Loco\" (Crazy), and dyed his hair green. He then became a celebrity. He was invited on to several television programs, many having poor ratings, and that looked for a \"sensational\" introduction or central topic.\n\nIn 1997, Poggi published his autobiography, \"''I Only Know I Am A Moron''\"(\"''Yo S\u00f3lo S\u00e9 Que Soy Un Imb\u00e9cil''), in a poor quality format with green ink and recurrent spelling, typographical and edition errors that according to the newspaper, El Siglo, was to show respect to the original message. It consisted of an introductory chapter with delusional quotes and some passages of his life \u2015 where he mixes popular characters and celebrities from the culture of Lima. The final chapter contained some of his drawings and some art critiques of his sculptures.\n\nIn 2000, Poggi participated in the filming of the movie ''My Nude Crime''\"(''Mi Crimen Al Desnudo''\"), by Le\u00f3nidas Zegarra, in which he played himself. The film was released in 2001. The project began in 1998, when a group of film students wanted to bring to the big screen the story of the murder of the serial criminal Angel D\u00edaz Balb\u00edn at the hands of psychologist Mario Poggi. Zegarra was invited to participate in the project as the director. The film's production was financed mainly by loans. The equipment needed was acquired in agreement with a production company. The budget, like in every movie by Zegarra, was  just $11.000 (equivalent to $16,388.72 as of 2019). Because of that, according to Zegarra, they came to an agreement with the actors and actresses (Mario Poggi, Am\u00e9rico Z\u00fa\u00f1iga, Yesabella, Rossi War, V\u00edctor \u00c1ngeles y Wilmer Ato) to pay them when the movie was commercialized, and when they retrieved the money invested. The movie also featured the well-known Peruvian singer [[La Tigresa del Oriente]] (In English: The Eastern Tigress) portraying [[Magaly Medina]], who became famous in the next decade for her music videos on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://larepublica.pe/blogs/camaleon_con_zapatillas/2009/09/25/la-otra-tigresa-del-oriente-la-felina-que-no-colgo-su-video-en-youtube/|title= La otra Tigresa del Oriente: la felina que no colg\u00f3 su video en Youtube | first = Alfredo | last = P\u00e9rez Andrade | date=September 25, 2008 | language = Spanish | trans-title = The other Eastern Tigress: the feline who did not upload her video on YouTube |publisher=La Rep\u00fablica| url-status = dead | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712062644/http://larepublica.pe/blogs/camaleon_con_zapatillas/2009/09/25/la-otra-tigresa-del-oriente-la-felina-que-no-colgo-su-video-en-youtube/|archive-date=July 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Death ===\nAccording the [[testimony]] of Poggi's brother, Mario Poggi suffered a cardiac arrest<ref name=\"Falleci\u00f33\"/> the night of February 25, 2016. He was taken to the [[:es:Hospital de Emergencias Jos\u00e9 Casimiro Ulloa|Casimiro Ulloa Hospital]], Lima. He died there of another cardiac arrest the next day at noon on February 26, 2016, just five days prior to his 73rd birthday.\n\nHis remains were laid in the Virgen de F\u00e1tima church in [[Miraflores District, Lima]].\n\n== Books ==\n\n* 1970: Mi Primer Pajazo. (My First Handjob)\n* 1975: Yo solo s\u00e9 que soy un imb\u00e9cil (I only know I'm a Moron) Autobiographic Text. Lima (Per\u00fa): Editorial El Siglo (The Century Publisher), 1997.\n* 1990s: El dec\u00e1logo de la correa vengadora (The Dechaloge of the Avenger Belt) Text on which he refers to the belt which he used in the Balbin's Killing.\n\n==Film==\n\n*2001: Mi crimen al desnudo (My Nude Crime). Directed by Leonidas Zegarra.\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Peruvian psychologists]]\n[[Category:People from Lima]]\n[[Category:Peruvian writers]]\n[[Category:Peruvian criminals]]\n[[Category:Peruvian murderers]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Carla.Abra", "label": "safe", "comment": "links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mario_Poggi"}
{"title_page": "Leon County, Florida", "text_new": "{{short description|County in Florida, United States}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county = Leon County\n| state = Florida\n| seal = Seal of Leon County, Florida.png\n| flag = Flag of Leon County, Florida.png\n| founded year = 1824\n| founded date = December 29\n| seat wl = Tallahassee\n| largest city wl = Tallahassee\n| area_total_sq_mi = 702\n| area_land_sq_mi = 667\n| area_water_sq_mi = 35\n| area percentage = 5.0%\n| census estimate yr = 2019\n| pop = 293582<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/leoncountyflorida/PST045218|title=U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts: Leon County, Florida|website=www.census.gov|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n| density_sq_mi = 435\n| named for = [[Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n]]\n| web = http://www.leoncountyfl.gov/\n| ex image = Leon County Courthouse (looking at SW corner).JPG\n| ex image cap = Leon County Courthouse\n| district = 2nd\n| district2 = 5th\n| time zone = Eastern\n}}\n\n'''Leon County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] located in the [[Florida Panhandle|Panhandle]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Florida]]. It was named after the Spanish explorer [[Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]], the population was 275,487.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/leoncountyflorida/PST045217|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 14, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630143208/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/12/12073.html|archivedate=June 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe [[county seat]] is [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]],<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> which is also the [[List of capitals in the United States|state capital]] and home of many politicians, lobbyists, jurists, and attorneys.\n\nLeon County is included in the [[Tallahassee metropolitan area]]. Tallahassee is home to two of Florida's major public universities, [[Florida State University]] and [[Florida A&M University]], as well as [[Tallahassee Community College]]. Together these institutions have a combined enrollment of more than 70,000 students annually, creating both economic and social effects.\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Leon County}}\nOriginally part of [[Escambia County, Florida|Escambia]] and later [[Gadsden County, Florida|Gadsden County]], Leon County was created in 1824.<ref>{{cite book|title=Publications of the Florida Historical Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WZQ-AAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA32|year=1908|publisher=Florida Historical Society.|page=32}}</ref> It was named after [[Juan Ponce de Le\u00f3n]], the [[Spain|Spanish]] [[List of explorers|explorer]] who was the first [[Europe]]an to reach Florida.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gannett|first=Henry|title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9V1IAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA185|year=1905|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=185}}</ref>\n\nThe United States finally acquired this territory in the nineteenth century. In the 1830s, it attempted to conduct [[Indian Removal]] of the [[Seminole]] and [[Creek people]]s, who had migrated south to escape European-American encroachment in Georgia and Alabama. After many Seminole were forcibly removed from the area or moved south to the Everglades during the [[Seminole Wars]], planters developed cotton plantations based on enslaved labor.\n\nBy the 1850s and 1860s, Leon County had become part of the \"cotton kingdom\" of the Deep South. It ranked fifth of all [[Florida]] and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] counties in the production of cotton from the 20 major plantations. Uniquely among Confederate capitals east of the [[Mississippi River]], in the [[American Civil War]] Tallahassee was never captured by Union forces. No Union soldiers set foot in Leon County until the [[Reconstruction Era]].\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|702|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|667|sqmi}} are land and {{convert|35|sqmi}} (5.0%) are water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref> Unlike much of Florida, most of Leon County has rolling hills, part of north Florida's [[Red Hills Region]]. The highest point is {{convert|280|ft|m}}, located in the northern part of the county.\n\n===Geology===\n[[File:Leon County Florida geological.png|thumb|Geological make-up of Leon County]]\n\nLeon County encompasses [[basement rock]] composed of [[basalt]]s of the [[Triassic]] and [[Jurassic]] from ~251\u2014145 million years ago interlayered with [[Mesozoic]] [[sedimentary rock]]s. The layers above the basement are [[carbonate rock]] created from dying [[foraminifera]], [[bryozoa]], [[mollusk]]s, and [[coral]]s from as early as the [[Paleocene]], a period of ~66\u201455.8 Ma.<ref>[http://www.clas.ufl.edu/users/guerry/GLY4155/sp35/Fgs35.HTM Geology of Florida, University of Florida] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091228042634/http://www.clas.ufl.edu/users/guerry/GLY4155/sp35/Fgs35.HTM |date=2009-12-28 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Eocene]] (~55.8\u201433.9 Ma) and [[Oligocene]] (~33.9\u201423 Ma), the [[Appalachian Mountains]] began to uplift and the erosion rate increased enough to fill the [[Gulf Trough]] with [[quartz sand]]s, [[silt]]s, and [[clay]]s via rivers and streams. The first sedimentation layer in Leon County is the Oligocene [[Suwannee Limestone]] in the southeastern part of the county as stated by the [[United States Geological Survey]] and [[Florida Geological Survey]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.usgs.gov/archive/sites/sofia.usgs.gov/|title=South Florida Information Access (SOFIA) -- USGS Greater Everglades Ecosystems Science|website=archive.usgs.gov|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Early Miocene]] (~23.03\u201415.7 Ma) sedimentation in Leon County is [[Hawthorn Group]], [[Torreya Formation]] and [[St. Marks Formation]] and found in the northern two-thirds of the county.\n\nThe [[Pliocene]] (~5.332\u20142.588 Ma) is represented by the [[Miccosukee Formation]] scattered within the Torreya Formation.\n\nSediments were laid down from the [[Pleistocene]] epoch (~2.588 million\u201412\u2009000 years ago) through [[Holocene]] epoch (~12,000\u2014present) and are designated [[Beach ridge and trail]] and [[undifferentiated sediments]].\n\n====Terraces and shorelines====\nDuring the Pleistocene, what would be Leon County emerged and submerged with each glacial and [[interglacial]] period. Interglacials created the topography of Leon as it is known now.\n\n''Also See [[Leon County Pleistocene coastal terraces]]''\n\n''Also see: [[Florida Platform]] and [[Lithostratigraphy]]''\n\n====Geologic formations====\n* [[Red Hills Region]] (North)\n* [[Cody Scarp]] (central)\n* [[Woodville Karst Plain]] (South)\n\n====Paleontology====\nThree sites within Leon County have yielded fossil remnants of the [[Miocene]] epoch. The Wikipedia article, \"[[Leon County, Florida paleontological sites]]\", provides more information about the Griscom Plantation Site, Seaboard Air Line Railroad Site, and Tallahassee Waterworks Site. It identifies fossils found at these sites by genus and species.\n\n===National protected area===\n* [[Apalachicola National Forest]] (part)\n\n===Bodies of water===\n* [[Lake Miccosukee]]\n* [[Black Creek (Leon County, Florida)|Black Creek]]\n* [[Lake Bradford]]\n* [[Lake Ella]]\n* [[Lake Hall]]\n* [[Lake Iamonia, Florida|Lake Iamonia]]\n* [[Lake Jackson (Tallahassee, Florida)|Lake Jackson]]\n* [[Lake Lafayette, Florida|Lake Lafayette]]\n* [[Lake Talquin]]\n* [[Ochlockonee River]]\n* [[Lake Munson]]\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n* [[Grady County, Georgia]] - north\n* [[Thomas County, Georgia]] - northeast\n* [[Jefferson County, Florida|Jefferson County]] - east\n* [[Wakulla County, Florida|Wakulla County]] - south\n* [[Gadsden County, Florida|Gadsden County]] - west\n* [[Liberty County, Florida|Liberty County]] - west\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 6494\n|1840= 10713\n|1850= 11442\n|1860= 12343\n|1870= 15236\n|1880= 19662\n|1890= 17752\n|1900= 19887\n|1910= 19427\n|1920= 18059\n|1930= 23476\n|1940= 31646\n|1950= 51590\n|1960= 74225\n|1970= 103047\n|1980= 148655\n|1990= 192493\n|2000= 239452\n|2010= 275487\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=293582\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2019\">{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/tables/2010-2019/counties/totals/|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/fl190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2019<ref name=\"QF\" />\n}}\n\n===Race===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-05-14|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2010, there were 275,487 people, and 108,592 households residing in the county. The [[population density]] was 413.2 people per square mile (159.5/km\u00b2). There were 123,423 housing units at an average density of 185 per square&nbsp;mile (71.4/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the county was 63.0% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 30.3% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.3% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 2.9% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], and 2.2% from two or more races. 5.6% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\n===Age===\nThere were 108,592 households out of which 24.2% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 36.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 13.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 45.8% were non-families. 31.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 6.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.29 and the average family size was 2.92.\n\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 20.0% under the age of 18, 26.3% from 18 to 24, 22.7% from 25 to 44, 22.4% from 45 to 64, and 8.7% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 27.8 years. For every 100 females, there were 91.57 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 89.03 males.\n\n===Education===\nThe adult citizens of Leon County enjoy the highest level of education in the state of Florida followed by [[Alachua County, Florida|Alachua County]] with a total of 67.8%.\n{| class=\"toccolours\"  style=\"fixed:right; margin-left:1em; width:380px;\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center; background:darkblue\" | <span style=\"color:white;\">'''Level of Education'''</span>\n|-\n| '''Level''' || '''Leon Co.''' || '''Florida''' || '''U.S.'''\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" |\n----\n|-\n| Some college or associate degree || 28.5% || 28.8% || 27.4%\n|-\n| Bachelor's Degree || 24.0% || 14.3% || 15.5%\n|-\n| Master's or Ph. D. || 17.7% || 8.1% || 8.9%\n|-\n| Total || 70.2% || 51.2% || 51.8%\n|\n|}\n''Source of above:''<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/educLevel.php?locIndex=8672|title=Leon County, FL - county education levels - ePodunk|website=www.epodunk.com|accessdate=October 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609134350/http://www.epodunk.com/cgi-bin/educLevel.php?locIndex=8672|archive-date=June 9, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Income===\nThe median income for a household in the county was $37,517, and the median income for a family was $52,962. Males had a median income of $35,235 versus $28,110 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $21,024. About 9.40% of families and 18.20% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 16.20% of those under age 18 and 8.20% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Accolades==\n* 2007 [http://www.nacpro.org/ National Association of County Park and Recreation Officials]' Environmental and Conservation Award for exceptional effort to reclaim, restore, preserve, acquire or develop unique and natural areas. Leon County has {{convert|1300|acre|km2}} of open space, [[forest]] and [[woodland]]s between the Miccosukee Canopy Road Greenway and J.R. Alford Greenway.\n\n==Law, government, and politics==\n\n===Politics===\n[[Image:LeonCoCrtHs2-16Sep2007.JPG|thumb|Leon County courthouse in [[Tallahassee]]; 2007]]\n\nFollowing Reconstruction, white Democrats regained power in Leon County and voters have historically voted for [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Party candidates at the national level. Tallahassee is one of the few cities in the [[Southern United States|South]] known for [[Progressivism|progressive]] [[activism]].\n\nThe county has voted Democratic in 24 out of the past 29 presidential elections since 1904. (Until the late 1960s, blacks were essentially [[Disfranchisement after Reconstruction era|disenfranchised]] in Florida and other Southern states.) Since the civil rights era, Tallahassee has elected black mayors and black state representatives.<ref>{{cite article\n|url=http://users.ipfw.edu/jehle/deisenbe/JHPcolumn/jhp102.pdf\n|title=In Tallahassee\n|magazine=[[Journal of Hispanic Philology]]\n|volume=10\n|number=2\n|first=Daniel\n|last=Eisenberg\n|year=1986\n|pages=97\u2013101\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006090302/http://users.ipfw.edu/jehle/deisenbe/JHPcolumn/jhp102.pdf |archive-date=October 6, 2014}}</ref> Its political affiliations likely draw from the high number of students, staff, and faculty associated with [[Florida State University]], [[Florida A&M University]], and [[Tallahassee Community College]] in Tallahassee, as well as the concentration of government employees in the capital city.\n\nLeon County has had the highest voter turnout of all counties in Florida. In the [[United States elections, 2008|2008 general election]], Leon County had a record setting [[early voting]] and [[vote by mail]] with a voter turnout of 85%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leonvotes.org/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810152722/http://www.leoncountyfl.gov/elect/|url-status=dead|title=Home - Leon County Supervisor of Elections|archivedate=August 10, 2014|website=www.leonvotes.org|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2, 2018, there were 112,572 Democrats, 58,083 Republicans, and 44,007 with other affiliations out of a total of 214,662 voters in Leon County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.leonvotes.org/|title=Home - Leon County Supervisor of Elections|website=www.leonvotes.org|accessdate=October 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"margin:auto; font-size:95